'''AI Superpowers: China, Silicon Valley, and the New World Order''' is a 2018 non-fiction book by [[Beijing]], [[China]]-based [[Kai-Fu Lee]], an [[Artificial Intelligence]] (AI) pioneer, expert on China and a [[venture capitalist]], and he previously held executive positions at [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], then [[Silicon Graphics|SGI]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Google]] before creating his own company, [http://www.sinovationventures.com/ Sinovation Ventures].<ref name="Forbes_Fannin_2017">{{citation |title=AI Superpowers By Kai-Fu Lee Defines A New World Order For Silicon Valley, China |first=Rebecca |last=Fannin |date=July 16, 2017 |publisher=Forbes}}</ref><ref name="NYT_Friedman_2018">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/25/opinion/trump-china-trade-economy-tech.html |title=Trump to China: ‘I Own You.’ Guess Again: The Chinese are catching up to the U.S. in many ways, and the president grasps only part of the reason |author=[[Thomas L. Friedman]] |series=Opinion |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 25, 2018 |access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>
== Themes == In his September 2018 ''[[The New York Times]]'' Opinion piece, [[Thomas L. Friedman]] cited ''AI Superpowers'' in his summary of the emerging global dominance of China in AI. According to Kai-Fu Lee, "If data is the new oil, then China is the new Saudi Arabia."<ref>{{cite book |title= AI Superpowers: China, Silicon Valley, and the New World Order| author= [[Kai-Fu Lee]]| publisher= [[Houghton Mifflin]]| date = September 25, 2018 | isbn= 9781328546395| oclc= 1035622189 ||location=[[Boston]], Mass}}</ref>
== Reception == Senator [[Mark Warner]] named ''AI Superpowers'' as his recommended book for The 2018 [[POLITICO]] 50 Reading List. <ref name="The POLITICO 50 Reading List">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2018/politico-50-book-picks/ |title=The POLITICO 50 Reading List |author=Politico Magazine Staff |newspaper=[[Politico]] |date=September 4, 2018 |access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>
