{{italic title}} {{Infobox book | name = Guyland | title_orig = | translator = | image = Guyland.jpg | image_size = 200px | author = [[Michael Kimmel]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Sociology]] | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[Harper (publisher)|Harper]] | release_date = 2008 | media_type = Print ([[hardcover]] and [[paperback]]) | pages = 356 | isbn = 978-0-06-083134-9 | preceded_by = [[The Gender of Desire: Essays on Masculinity]] | followed_by = [[Privilege: a reader]] }}
'''''Guyland: The Perilous World Where Boys Become Men''''' ({{ISBN|978-0-06-083134-9}}) is a book by [[Michael Kimmel]], published in 2008. The book covers the culture for young men transitioning from [[adolescence]] to [[adulthood]].<ref name="msnbc">{{cite web |url= http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/26317942#.T7Et4r_-4nQ |title= Boys to men: Why guys aren't growing up |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= August 27, 2008|work= [[MSNBC]] |publisher= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kzgSokNt|archivedate=2009-11-02| accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>
Kimmel interviewed 400 men aged 16 to 26 and identified a trend whereby young men increasingly delay adulthood.<ref name="edmonton">{{cite web |url= http://m.edmontonsun.com/2011/10/05/boys-will-be-boys|title= Boys will be boys |last1= Jacobs |first1= Mindelle |last2= |first2= |date= October 5, 2011 |work= [[Edmonton Sun]] |publisher= |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/07/style/tmagazine/07brubach.html?pagewanted=all|title= Dudes in Guyland |last1= Brubach |first1= Holly |last2= |first2= |date= September 4, 2008|work= [[The New York Times]] |publisher= |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> Kimmel notes that, in 1960, almost 70% of American men had by the age of 30 left home, completed their educations, found a partner and started work. By comparison, today less than a third of men reach these milestones before their thirties. Kimmel writes that young men are reluctant to grow up because they "see grown-up life as such a loss".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2008/08/30/why-i-am-leaving-guyland.html|title= Why I Am Leaving Guyland |last1= Dokoupil |first1= Tony |last2= |first2= |date= August 28, 2008|work= [[Newsweek]] |publisher= |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref> In order to avoid the responsibilities of adulthood, young men retreat into a [[homosociality|homosocial]] world Kimmel terms "Guyland", a social space and a stage of life where "guys gather to be guys with each other, unhassled by the demands of parents, girlfriends, jobs, kids, and the other nuisances of adult life".<ref name="msnbc"/> Young white men, in particular, feel a sense of "thwarted entitlement", believing that women and minorities have taken away traditionally white male jobs and positions.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.salon.com/2008/09/17/guyland/ |title= Dude, where's my manhood? |last1= Hannaham |first1= James |last2= |first2= |date= September 17, 2008|work= [[Salon (website)]] |publisher= |accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name="edmonton"/>
