{{Spanish name|Ballester|Boix}}
'''Manuel Ballester Boix''' (born in [[Barcelona]] on June 27, 1919; died April 5, 2005) was a Spanish chemist.

==Biography==
He received his degree at the [[University of Barcelona]] in 1944, his doctorate in Madrid, and finished his training at [[Harvard University]] in 1951.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/premios/1982/manuel-ballester-boix/text/|title=Manuel Ballester Boix - Fundación Príncipe de Asturias|date=2009-10-09|access-date=2017-08-07|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009233424/http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/premios/1982/manuel-ballester-boix/text/|archivedate=2009-10-09|df=}}</ref> In 1944 he formed a team at the [[Spanish National Research Council]]. His work has largely been in kinetics and [[organic chemistry]].<ref>[http://fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/en/awards/1982/manuel-ballester-boix-1/text/ Bio at the Prince of Asturias Foundation] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120709041551/http://fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/en/awards/1982/manuel-ballester-boix-1/text/ |date=2012-07-09 }}</ref>

==Awards==
*1982 - [[Prince of Asturias Awards#Technical and Scientific Research|Prince of Asturias Award for Technical and Scientific Research]]

