{{Infobox mine | name = Çöpler mine | image = | width = | caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_label = | pushpin_map_caption = | coordinates = | place = | subdivision_type = | state/province = [[Erzincan Province]] | country = [[Turkey]] | owner = | stock_exchange = | stock_code = | official website = | acquisition year = | products = [[Gold]] | financial year = | amount = | opening year = | closing year = }} The '''Çöpler mine''' is one of the largest [[gold]] mines in [[Turkey]] and in the world, operated by the American [[Çalık_Holding#Mining|Alacer Gold Corporation]].<ref name=usgs>{{Cite journal| pages = 27| last = Hastorun| first = Sinan| title = The Mineral Industry of Turkey |publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|url=https://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/country/2014/myb3-2014-tu.pdf}}</ref><ref name="Kiruna">{{cite web|url=http://www.gbreports.com/admin/reports/EMJ-Turkey2012.pdf|title=Turkey minerals|year=2013|publisher=gbreports.com|accessdate=2013-07-03}}</ref> The mine is located in [[Erzincan Province]].<ref name="Kiruna"/> The mine has estimated reserves of 6 million oz of [[gold]].<ref name="Kiruna"/>
Çöpler is an [[epithermal]] [[Porphyry copper deposit|porphyry]] copper-gold deposit which forms part of the Middle Eocene [[Çöpler–Kabataş magmatic complex]] in central-eastern Turkey which formed on the north-eastern margin of the [[Tauride-Anatolide microcontinent]]. The intrusive rocks at Çöpler were emplaced into Late Paleozoic-Mesozoic metamorphosed sedimentary rocks. Dating of igneous rocks indicate a brief magmatic and hydrothermal history at Çöpler less than a million year long about 43.8–44.6&nbsp;[[Million years ago|Ma]]. The composition of magma indicate it was generated in a [[convergent boundary|convergent margin]]. Çöpler is, however, located to far away from the [[Maden–Helete arc]] and therefore must have formed in a [[Back-arc basin|back-arc setting]], similar to that in the [[Bingham Canyon Mine]], Utah.<ref>{{Harvnb|İmer|Richards|Creaser|2013|loc=Abstract}}</ref>
